                <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 812.00/2888a.</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of State</gloss> to
                        the <gloss type="to">American Ambassador</gloss>
                    </hi>.</head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.—Extract.]</seg>
                </opener>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1912-02-25T19:00:00-05:00">
                            <hi rend="italic">February 25, 1912—7 p.m.</hi>
                        </date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Newspapers report that there are at Juárez only 100 Federals to oppose a large
                    insurrectionary force. Would not the Mexican <pb facs="0995" n="879"
                        xml:id="pg_879"/> Government, understanding that further firing into El Paso
                    would be intolerable, be disposed spontaneously to give such orders as would
                    preclude the possibility of fighting in Juárez or its immediate vicinity?</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Huntington Wilson.</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
